vectorData.altText: 6. Venous blood-filled spaces associated with the cranial meninges are called ___________ __________ ________________.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.
That’s right! Dural venous sinuses form along the lines of attachment of the cranial meninges.

Like the spinal cord, the brain is covered by three layers of meninges: 
a) a tough outer layer (dura mater), 
b) an intermediate spider - web like layer (the arachnoid mater), and 
c) a thin, delicate layer (pia mater) that adheres to the brain and spinal cord. 
Like the spinal cord, the pia is thin and closely adhered to the surface of the brain. The arachnoid is a looser covering, and the CSF-filled subarachnoid space separates the pia and the arachnoid. Similar to the lumbar cistern associated with the spinal cord, in some places the subarachnoid space surrounding the brain is expanded, forming CSF-filled subarachnoid cisterns.
Unlike the spinal cord, associated with the cranial meninges are venous blood-filled spaces, called the dural venous sinuses. These are not called “veins” because, as you know from your histology eModules, veins are trilaminar structures, consisting of a tunica intima, tunica media and tunica adventitia (externa). The venous-blood filled spaces associated with the cranial meninges do not have this structure, and so cannot be called veins. Because they contain blood, however, they are lined by endothelium.
